<br>
While I didn't petition these guys' names, I do see the harm they'd be bringing; not to other players, but to Sony/VI itself.<br>
<br>
The reason for the name policy forbidding copyrighted/trademarked names is to prevent Sony from being sued for millions upon millions of dollars.  In this context, Sony can and would be considered a publisher.  Furthermore, they're making a profit off of this &quot;publication&quot;, so they don't fall under the &quot;personal use&quot; clause of the Fair Use laws.  Even futher, they are responsible for any copyright violations any player commits--just like a newspaper or magazine would be for copyright violations their writers commit.  I admit the odds that the copyright holder would hear about this are slim.  On the other hand, the odds that the copyright holder would sue as soon as he/she/they hear about this are high.  And I'd put the odds in the copyright holder's favor for winning or settling for tons of money.<br>
<br>
Granted, they use celebrity names and anagrams of names all the time--but I'm also sure their team of on-retainer lawyers has OK'd every last one of those.<br>
<br>
I thought about the issue of how these are actually historical names of Renaissance artists, and to a certain extent, that argument *might* work for Sony in a court of law--but it also might not.  The countering argument would be that these five travelled together, and were intending to represent the likeness of the Teenage Mutant Ninja Turtles; that much is clear to everyone who encountered them.  That's the point where you've crossed from adopting historical names into trademark/copyright infringement.  Sony might be able to win the case in a court of law, but I wouldn't put the odds in their favor, and most likely it'd result in a multi-million dollar settlement out of court.<br>
<br>
The problem isn't that the GMs are overreacting here.  The problem is that these names, in this particular configuration, would cost the company millions of dollars--and the names would still have to go.<br>
<br>
(None of this is to say I'm glad they did this, by the way.  I'm just explaining a) what are their most likely reasons for doing it and b) why they're most likely not going to reconsider this decision.)<br>
